The Nexus Q really is a device
for streaming music and video

00:46:27.900 --> 00:46:30.040
from Google Play and
from YouTube.

00:46:30.040 --> 00:46:34.250
And Google TV is really a
platform that integrates web

00:46:34.250 --> 00:46:37.500
and applications and linear TV
and is built into lots of

00:46:37.500 --> 00:46:39.230
different devices, TVs,
and buddy boxes.

00:46:39.230 --> 00:46:43.120
So they're solving different
problems right now, and we

00:46:43.120 --> 00:46:45.985
can't really comment on how or
whether they might merge or

00:46:45.985 --> 00:46:47.235
come together in the future.

00:46:49.570 --> 00:46:52.050
OSSAMA ALAMI: We'll do another
one from here.

00:46:52.050 --> 00:46:55.320
AUDIENCE: I have a question
about content.

00:46:55.320 --> 00:46:57.850
As you said, content is king.

00:46:57.850 --> 00:47:01.230
And we really don't have
that much content

00:47:01.230 --> 00:47:03.900
outside of the US.

00:47:03.900 --> 00:47:06.570
And that goes for the entire--

00:47:06.570 --> 00:47:08.000
the Play experience.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:12.620
So Nexus Q is a perfect example
for a device that just

00:47:12.620 --> 00:47:15.100
won't work outside of the US.

00:47:15.100 --> 00:47:20.770
And Google TV has the same
problem, because people don't

00:47:20.770 --> 00:47:25.860
have any incentive to buy
one outside of the US.

00:47:25.860 --> 00:47:34.010
I was wondering if you guys had
a master plan to fix that?

00:47:34.010 --> 00:47:35.470
OSSAMA ALAMI: You know, it's
something that we're

00:47:35.470 --> 00:47:39.240
constantly working on, local
content and bringing more

00:47:39.240 --> 00:47:43.200
content to TV, both in the
US and internationally.

00:47:43.200 --> 00:47:48.830
I think in many ways, we look to
the developer community to

00:47:48.830 --> 00:47:51.470
help bring that content,
especially local

00:47:51.470 --> 00:47:53.910
content, to the TV.

00:47:53.910 --> 00:47:58.540
That's why we built a platform
that you can easily build for.

00:47:58.540 --> 00:48:01.770
But there isn't anything that I
can comment on in terms of a

00:48:01.770 --> 00:48:04.800
master plan to work on that.

00:48:04.800 --> 00:48:07.900
MICHAEL SUNDER MEYER: I really
believe that a lot of the

00:48:07.900 --> 00:48:09.990
revolution is going to happen
outside of the US, especially

00:48:09.990 --> 00:48:12.250
because there's so many
different experiments already

00:48:12.250 --> 00:48:16.030
happening in the UK and France
and Korea where they've got

00:48:16.030 --> 00:48:17.370
pure IP TV plays.

00:48:17.370 --> 00:48:19.960
And they've got to Catchup
TV already on the web.

00:48:19.960 --> 00:48:23.620
And so we really look to
countries outside the US to

00:48:23.620 --> 00:48:26.520
help propel it as well
as inside the US.

00:48:26.520 --> 00:48:28.845
So you can be sure we're looking
at that very closely.

00:48:28.845 --> 00:48:30.092
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:30.092 --> 00:48:32.400
OSSAMA ALAMI: Why don't we
do a question from here?

00:48:32.400 --> 00:48:34.940
AUDIENCE: Guys, thanks for
rolling out to Australia.

00:48:34.940 --> 00:48:37.040
You might not have
had a choice.

00:48:37.040 --> 00:48:39.680
It would be great if you could
have lunch with the Google

00:48:39.680 --> 00:48:41.880
Music people and sort
of encourage them

00:48:41.880 --> 00:48:43.120
to do the same thing.

00:48:43.120 --> 00:48:44.690
That would be awesome.

00:48:44.690 --> 00:48:46.320
So question--

00:48:46.320 --> 00:48:50.010
accessibility in Google TV,
is it early days yet?

00:48:50.010 --> 00:48:53.120
I saw a great talk yesterday
about Jelly Bean

00:48:53.120 --> 00:48:55.135
accessibility, and things have
really come forward.

00:48:57.760 --> 00:49:00.440
Obviously the blind and
television doesn't really work

00:49:00.440 --> 00:49:04.110
so much, but you've got captions
for hearing impaired

00:49:04.110 --> 00:49:05.670
and so forth.

00:49:05.670 --> 00:49:08.490
Has there been much work
done on that, or is

00:49:08.490 --> 00:49:12.030
it a bit too early?

00:49:12.030 --> 00:49:14.040
MICHAEL SUNDER MEYER: We're
built on Android, so when we

00:49:14.040 --> 00:49:16.500
upgrade to the next version
of Android, we get all the

00:49:16.500 --> 00:49:16.980
accessibility.

00:49:16.980 --> 00:49:20.420
So we're really looking to the
Android team for most of those

00:49:20.420 --> 00:49:21.460
platform capabilities.

00:49:21.460 --> 00:49:22.550
And we'll take advantage
of them as

00:49:22.550 --> 00:49:23.990
soon as they're available.

00:49:23.990 --> 00:49:27.510
OSSAMA ALAMI: But stuff that's
uniquely video-oriented is

00:49:27.510 --> 00:49:31.748
stuff that we're focusing on,
like closed captioning.

00:49:31.748 --> 00:49:33.620
Take a question here.

00:49:33.620 --> 00:49:36.040
AUDIENCE: It seems to me
before Google TV can go

00:49:36.040 --> 00:49:39.980
mainstream, you probably need
a different input method.

00:49:39.980 --> 00:49:41.990
Something like a
simple joystick

00:49:41.990 --> 00:49:43.520
would be a lot easier.

00:49:43.520 --> 00:49:48.780
Are you guys experimenting with
different input methods?

00:49:48.780 --> 00:49:50.695
Because a keyboard is--

00:49:50.695 --> 00:49:53.295
you don't want that sitting
in the living room.

00:49:53.295 --> 00:49:53.780
MICHAEL SUNDER MEYER:
Yeah, we're

00:49:53.780 --> 00:49:54.630
definitely aware of that.

00:49:54.630 --> 00:49:57.680
We learned a lot of lessons
from the first generation.

00:49:57.680 --> 00:50:00.140
Although, it's interesting that
a lot of people actually

00:50:00.140 --> 00:50:02.860
do want-- it's a narrow
population, but for some

00:50:02.860 --> 00:50:04.060
people, a keyboard
is really great.

00:50:04.060 --> 00:50:07.890
So as an accessory you can buy
for your TV to do a lot of

00:50:07.890 --> 00:50:08.930
input, it's great.

00:50:08.930 --> 00:50:11.360
But definitely agree with you
that the main interaction

00:50:11.360 --> 00:50:13.460
model, we need to evolve that.

00:50:13.460 --> 00:50:17.010
And I would love to bring
something closer to touch, or

00:50:17.010 --> 00:50:18.150
we may leap beyond.

00:50:18.150 --> 00:50:20.240
But we can't comment on exactly
what we're doing, but

00:50:20.240 --> 00:50:22.800
we're definitely spending
a lot of cycles on that.

00:50:22.800 --> 00:50:24.050
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

