you gave and taking into account
the fragments API that

00:50:32.485 --> 00:50:35.890
was introduced in Honeycomb to
try and unify the APKs-- like

00:50:35.890 --> 00:50:39.320
Flixster takes advantage of
that to have one APK that

00:50:39.320 --> 00:50:42.400
works both on phone
and tablet.

00:50:42.400 --> 00:50:45.110
Is there any way that you guys
would hook into default

00:50:45.110 --> 00:50:49.350
fragments that if people use
them, you could sort of build

00:50:49.350 --> 00:50:50.880
in some of these
design things?

00:50:50.880 --> 00:50:53.200
Like it would automatically
have a darker

00:50:53.200 --> 00:50:53.980
screen behind it.

00:50:53.980 --> 00:50:56.425
It would automatically
transition the text to

00:50:56.425 --> 00:50:59.730
slightly larger in list
view, stuff like that.

00:50:59.730 --> 00:51:02.035
OSSAMA ALAMI: I think
we're careful.

00:51:04.800 --> 00:51:06.040
We are an Android device.

00:51:06.040 --> 00:51:09.990
So we're careful in not
making assumptions on

00:51:09.990 --> 00:51:12.140
behalf of the developer.

00:51:12.140 --> 00:51:17.040
So we do publish samples and
libraries that make it easier

00:51:17.040 --> 00:51:21.010
to get started and sort of
have our UI principles

00:51:21.010 --> 00:51:22.610
embedded in them.

00:51:22.610 --> 00:51:30.650
But in terms of changing the
default behavior of certain

00:51:30.650 --> 00:51:34.130
Android widgets and fragments,
that's not something that

00:51:34.130 --> 00:51:37.220
we're looking to do.

00:51:37.220 --> 00:51:38.700
MICHAEL SUNDER MEYER: So like
I said, I think we're really

00:51:38.700 --> 00:51:40.640
at the beginning of even
figuring out how to make great

00:51:40.640 --> 00:51:44.130
designs on TV that can perform
on all these devices.

00:51:44.130 --> 00:51:46.820
And as we learn patterns, we
are really interested in

00:51:46.820 --> 00:51:50.640
figuring out ways to get them
into your hands either if it's

00:51:50.640 --> 00:51:53.560
just a document that's written
about how to do it, code

00:51:53.560 --> 00:51:55.480
snippets, examples.

00:51:55.480 --> 00:52:00.360
And so over time, I'm really
committed to trying to get

00:52:00.360 --> 00:52:01.560
that out there.

00:52:01.560 --> 00:52:04.400
We win if the applications
are great.

00:52:04.400 --> 00:52:07.310
And whatever we can do to
support that, we will try.

00:52:07.310 --> 00:52:10.150
But we're not at a point
where we have

00:52:10.150 --> 00:52:12.660
anything to announce yet.

00:52:12.660 --> 00:52:13.530
OSSAMA ALAMI: Over here.

00:52:13.530 --> 00:52:17.270
AUDIENCE: So you guys mentioned
that personalization

00:52:17.270 --> 00:52:18.330
is really important.

00:52:18.330 --> 00:52:22.500
But the TV is basically the most
impersonal object in the

00:52:22.500 --> 00:52:26.330
home, whereas everybody
in the family uses it.

00:52:26.330 --> 00:52:28.940
A computer is really good at
handling multiple users.

00:52:28.940 --> 00:52:31.810
A tablet is really good at being
a single-user device.

00:52:31.810 --> 00:52:34.780
A phone is being owned
by a single person.

00:52:34.780 --> 00:52:39.120
But the TV, it's something that
everybody wants to use.

00:52:39.120 --> 00:52:44.220
So how do you manage the balance
between allowing

00:52:44.220 --> 00:52:47.090
everybody to have a very
personal experience with still

00:52:47.090 --> 00:52:50.130
managing the fact they you don't
want to alienate anybody

00:52:50.130 --> 00:52:51.115
that uses the device?

00:52:51.115 --> 00:52:53.440
MICHAEL SUNDER MEYER: Yeah.

00:52:53.440 --> 00:52:55.850
Yeah, the fact that it's shared
list doesn't mean that

00:52:55.850 --> 00:52:56.660
it can't be personal.

00:52:56.660 --> 00:52:58.840
I think it can do both.

00:52:58.840 --> 00:53:00.250
Like the shelves that we talked

00:53:00.250 --> 00:53:03.180
about and adding favorites.

00:53:03.180 --> 00:53:05.920
We're looking at ways to add
favorites for each person in

00:53:05.920 --> 00:53:06.480
the household.

00:53:06.480 --> 00:53:09.560
So it's still personal, but it's
personal to each person.

00:53:09.560 --> 00:53:13.050
Also looking at ways that we
can understand who's in the

00:53:13.050 --> 00:53:16.710
room and give recommendations
that are different for two

00:53:16.710 --> 00:53:18.480
people than might be
for each individual

00:53:18.480 --> 00:53:20.380
person, find overlaps.

00:53:20.380 --> 00:53:21.630
So there's a number
of different ways

00:53:21.630 --> 00:53:22.210
we're looking at that.

00:53:22.210 --> 00:53:22.870
But yeah, you're right.

00:53:22.870 --> 00:53:25.970
It's a shared device, but we
still want to make that

00:53:25.970 --> 00:53:28.300
experience personal for the
people that are in the room at

00:53:28.300 --> 00:53:29.550
any given time.

